The companion text Using R for Introductory Econometrics by Florian Heiss provides specific R scripts in support of the main text and the inspiration for my scripts, notes and graphics. I will reference this document as (Heiss). The following is from Part 1 - Regression Analysis with Cross-Sectional Data, Chapter 8 Heteroscedasticity of (Heiss).

8 Heteroscedasticity

8.1 Heteroscedasticity-Robust inference

(Wooldridge) presents a derivation of \(Var(\hat{\beta_{1}})\) when heteroskedasticity is present (Equation 8.4, page 245) based on White(1980). (Heiss) suggests the function car::hccm() (heteroscedasticity-corrected covariance matrices) that offers serveral versions of the White formula.

Since the variance of \(\hat{\beta_{i}}\) influences the standard errors, t statistics, and \(p\) values, (Wooldridge) suggest the lmtest::coeftest() which accepts an argument for incorporating Whites estimates of the variance-covariance matrix of the coefficients.

For performing \(F\)-test, (Wooldridge) notes that car::linearHypothesis() function also accepts an argument for incorporating Whites estimates.

Task: Compare the usual estimates of variance-covariance and associated tests with Whites estimates when heteroscedasticity is suggested in the data.
  1. Set up the data:
data("gpa3", package="wooldridge")
gpa3_dt <- data.table::setDT(gpa3)
gpa3_dt <- gpa3_dt[spring == 1, .(cumgpa, sat, hsperc, tothrs, female, black, white)]
  1. Define the linear model:
formula_obj <- cumgpa ~ sat + hsperc + tothrs + female + black + white
  1. Estimate the ols:
gpa3_ols <- RregressPkg::ols_calc(df = gpa3_dt, formula_obj = formula_obj)
RplotterPkg::create_table(gpa3_ols$coef_df)

  1. Estimate the variance-covariance and ols statistics with Whites formulas:
gpa3_lm <- lm(formula_obj, data = gpa3_dt)
lmtest::coeftest(gpa3_lm, vcov=car::hccm)

Task: Compute the \(F\)-tests with both the regular and Whites alternative variance-covariance estimates using car::linearHypothesis().
  1. Set the null hypothesis that black = white = 0
null_hypoth <- c("black","white")
  1. Compute the regular \(F\)-test:
car::linearHypothesis(gpa3_lm, null_hypoth)
## Linear hypothesis test
## 
## Hypothesis:
## black = 0
## white = 0
## 
## Model 1: restricted model
## Model 2: cumgpa ~ sat + hsperc + tothrs + female + black + white
## 
##   Res.Df    RSS Df Sum of Sq      F Pr(>F)
## 1    361 79.362                           
## 2    359 79.062  2   0.29934 0.6796 0.5075
  1. Compute the \(F\)-test with Whites estimates for variance-covariance:
car::linearHypothesis(gpa3_lm, null_hypoth, vcov=car::hccm)

8.2 Heteroscedasticity tests

Task: Investigate Heteroskedasticity in a Housing Price Equation.
  1. Set up the data:
data("hprice1", package = "wooldridge")
hprice1_dt <- data.table::setDT(hprice1)
hprice1_dt <- hprice1_dt[, .(price, lotsize, sqrft, bdrms)]
  1. Define the model formula:
formula_obj <- price ~ lotsize + sqrft + bdrms
  1. Plot the model residuals:
RregressPkg::plot_residuals_check(
  df = hprice1_dt,
  formula_obj = formula_obj,
  residual_label_threshold = 150.0,
  leverage_label_threshold = 30.0,
  title = "Housing Price Model Residuals"
)

## TableGrob (3 x 2) "plots_table": 5 grobs
##   z     cells        name               grob
## 1 1 (1-1,1-2) plots_table text[GRID.text.11]
## 2 2 (2-2,1-1) plots_table     gtable[layout]
## 3 3 (3-3,1-1) plots_table     gtable[layout]
## 4 4 (2-2,2-2) plots_table     gtable[layout]
## 5 5 (3-3,2-2) plots_table     gtable[layout]
  1. Run Breusch-Pagan Test for Heteroskedasticity:
BP_test_df <- RregressPkg::ols_BP_test_calc(
  df = hprice1_dt,
  formula_obj = formula_obj
)
RplotterPkg::create_table(
  x = BP_test_df,
  caption = "BP Test Housing Price Residuals"
)
BP Test Housing Price Residuals
Statistic Value p.Value
F 5.338919 0.002047744
LM 14.092386 0.002782060
Take Away: The \(p-values\) indicate strong evidence against the null hypothesis of homoskedasticity of variance. The square of the estimated error term is a function of the predictor coefficients.


Logarithmic functional form of the formula object

Chapter 6 of Introductory Econometrics suggest a reduction of heteroskedasticity by using the logarithmic functional form.

  1. Define the model formula:
log_formula_obj <- log(price) ~ log(lotsize) + log(sqrft) + bdrms
  1. Plot the model residuals:
RregressPkg::plot_residuals_check(
  df = hprice1_dt,
  formula_obj = log_formula_obj,
  residual_label_threshold = 0.4,
  leverage_label_threshold = 0.15,
  title = "Log Housing Price Model Residuals"
)

## TableGrob (3 x 2) "plots_table": 5 grobs
##   z     cells        name                grob
## 1 1 (1-1,1-2) plots_table text[GRID.text.202]
## 2 2 (2-2,1-1) plots_table      gtable[layout]
## 3 3 (3-3,1-1) plots_table      gtable[layout]
## 4 4 (2-2,2-2) plots_table      gtable[layout]
## 5 5 (3-3,2-2) plots_table      gtable[layout]
  1. Run Breusch-Pagan Test for Heteroskedasticity:
BP_test_df <- RregressPkg::ols_BP_test_calc(
  df = hprice1_dt,
  formula_obj = log_formula_obj
)
RplotterPkg::create_table(
  x = BP_test_df,
  caption = "BP Test Log Housing Price Residuals"
)
BP Test Log Housing Price Residuals
Statistic Value p.Value
F 1.411500 0.2451457
LM 4.223246 0.2383448
Take Away: Based on the \(p-values\) we fail to reject the null hypothesis where the square of the estimated error term is not a function of the predictor coefficients.
